# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: vertical-pod-autoscaling
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:vertical-pod-autoscaling/autoscaling] Autoscaling differs from having a fixed daily, weekly, or yearly cycle of server use in that it is responsive to actual usage patterns, and thus reduces the potential downside of having too few or too many servers for the traffic load.
[src:vertical-pod-autoscaling/autoscaling] For instance, if traffic is usually lower at midnight, then a static scaling solution might schedule some servers to sleep at night, but this might result in downtime on a night where people happen to use the Internet more (for instance, due to a viral news event).
[src:vertical-pod-autoscaling/autoscaling] Autoscaling, on the other hand, can handle unexpected traffic spikes better.
[src:vertical-pod-autoscaling/autoscaling] In the list below, we use the terminology used by Amazon Web Services (AWS).
[src:vertical-pod-autoscaling/autoscaling] However, alternative names are noted and terminology that is specific to the names of Amazon services is not used for the names.
[src:vertical-pod-autoscaling/autoscaling] Amazon Web Services launched the Amazon Elastic Compute Cloud (EC2) service in August 2006, that allowed developers to programmatically create and terminate instances (machines).
[src:vertical-pod-autoscaling/autoscaling] At the time of initial launch, AWS did not offer autoscaling, but the ability to programmatically create and terminate instances gave developers the flexibility to write their own code for autoscaling.
[src:vertical-pod-autoscaling/autoscaling] Third-party autoscaling software for AWS began appearing around April 2008.
[src:vertical-pod-autoscaling/autoscaling] These included tools by Scalr and RightScale.
[src:vertical-pod-autoscaling/autoscaling] RightScale was used by Animoto, which was able to handle Facebook traffic by adopting autoscaling.
[src:vertical-pod-autoscaling/autoscaling] On May 18, 2009, Amazon launched its own autoscaling feature along with Elastic Load Balancing, as part of Amazon Elastic Compute Cloud.
[src:vertical-pod-autoscaling/autoscaling] Autoscaling is now an integral component of Amazon's EC2 offering.
[src:vertical-pod-autoscaling/autoscaling] Autoscaling on Amazon Web Services is done through a web browser or the command line tool.
[src:vertical-pod-autoscaling/autoscaling] In May 2016 Autoscaling was also offered in AWS ECS Service.
[src:vertical-pod-autoscaling/autoscaling] On-demand video provider Netflix documented their use of autoscaling with Amazon Web Services to meet their highly variable consumer needs.
[src:vertical-pod-autoscaling/autoscaling] They found that aggressive scaling up and delayed and cautious scaling down served their goals of uptime and responsiveness best.
[src:vertical-pod-autoscaling/autoscaling] In an article for *TechCrunch*, Zev Laderman, the co-founder and CEO of Newvem, a service that helps optimize AWS cloud infrastructure, recommended that startups use autoscaling in order to keep their Amazon Web Services costs low.
[src:vertical-pod-autoscaling/autoscaling] Various best practice guides for AWS use suggest using its autoscaling feature even in cases where the load is not variable.
[src:vertical-pod-autoscaling/autoscaling] Netflix's internal best practices require every instance to be in an autoscaling group, and its conformity monkey terminates any instance not in an autoscaling group in order to enforce this best practice.
[src:vertical-pod-autoscaling/autoscaling] On June 27, 2013, Microsoft announced that it was adding autoscaling support to its Windows Azure cloud computing platform.
[src:vertical-pod-autoscaling/autoscaling] Documentation for the feature is available on the Microsoft Developer Network.
[src:vertical-pod-autoscaling/autoscaling] Oracle Cloud Platform allows server instances to automatically scale a cluster in or out by defining an auto-scaling rule.
[src:vertical-pod-autoscaling/autoscaling] These rules are based on CPU and/or memory utilization and determine when to add or remove nodes.
[src:vertical-pod-autoscaling/autoscaling] On November 17, 2014, the Google Compute Engine announced a public beta of its autoscaling feature for use in Google Cloud Platform applications.
[src:vertical-pod-autoscaling/autoscaling] As of March 2015, the autoscaling tool is still in Beta.
[src:vertical-pod-autoscaling/autoscaling] In a blog post in August 2014, a Facebook engineer disclosed that the company had started using autoscaling to bring down its energy costs.
[src:vertical-pod-autoscaling/autoscaling] The blog post reported a 27% decline in energy use for low traffic hours (around midnight) and a 10-15% decline in energy use over the typical 24-hour cycle.
[src:vertical-pod-autoscaling/autoscaling] Autoscaling by default uses *reactive* decision approach for dealing with traffic scaling: scaling only happens in response to real-time changes in metrics.
[src:vertical-pod-autoscaling/autoscaling] In some cases, particularly when the changes occur very quickly, this reactive approach to scaling is insufficient.
[src:vertical-pod-autoscaling/autoscaling] Two other kinds of autoscaling decision approaches are described below.
[src:vertical-pod-autoscaling/autoscaling] This is an approach to autoscaling where changes are made to the minimum size, maximum size, or desired capacity of the autoscaling group at specific times of day.
[src:vertical-pod-autoscaling/autoscaling] Scheduled scaling is useful, for instance, if there is a known traffic load increase or decrease at specific times of the day, but the change is too sudden for reactive approach based autoscaling to respond fast enough.
[src:vertical-pod-autoscaling/autoscaling] AWS autoscaling groups support scheduled scaling.
[src:vertical-pod-autoscaling/autoscaling] This approach to autoscaling uses predictive analytics.
[src:vertical-pod-autoscaling/autoscaling] The idea is to combine recent usage trends with historical usage data as well as other kinds of data to predict usage in the future, and autoscale based on these predictions.
[src:vertical-pod-autoscaling/autoscaling] For parts of their infrastructure and specific workloads, Netflix found that Scryer, their predictive analytics engine, gave better results than Amazon's reactive autoscaling approach.
[src:vertical-pod-autoscaling/autoscaling] On November 20, 2018, AWS announced that predictive scaling would be available as part of its autoscaling offering.
[src:vertical-pod-autoscaling/capacity-management] As the usage of IT services change and functionality evolves, the amount of central processing units (CPUs), memory and storage to a physical or virtual server etc. also changes.
[src:vertical-pod-autoscaling/capacity-management] If there are spikes in, for example, processing power at a particular time of the day, it proposes analyzing what is happening at that time and making changes to maximize the existing IT infrastructure; for example, tuning the application, or moving a batch cycle to a quieter period.
[src:vertical-pod-autoscaling/capacity-management] This capacity planning identifies any potential capacity related issues likely to arise, and justifies any necessary investment decisions - for example, the server requirements to accommodate future IT resource demand, or a data center consolidation.
[src:vertical-pod-autoscaling/capacity-management] These activities are intended to optimize performance and efficiency, and to plan for and justify financial investments.
[src:vertical-pod-autoscaling/capacity-management] Capacity management interacts with the discipline of Performance Engineering, both during the requirements and design activities of building a system, and when using performance monitoring.
[src:vertical-pod-autoscaling/capacity-management] As data is broken into component parts (often known frames, packets, or segments) for transmission, several factors can affect their delivery.
[src:vertical-pod-autoscaling/capacity-management] These factors, and others (such as the performance of the network signaling on the end nodes, compression, encryption, concurrency, and so on) all affect the effective performance of a network.
[src:vertical-pod-autoscaling/capacity-management] In some cases, the network may not work at all; in others, it may be slow or unusable.
[src:vertical-pod-autoscaling/capacity-management] And because applications run over these networks, application performance suffers.
[src:vertical-pod-autoscaling/capacity-management] Various intelligent solutions are available to ensure that traffic over the network is effectively managed to optimize performance for all users.
[src:vertical-pod-autoscaling/capacity-management] Network performance management (NPM) consists of measuring, modeling, planning, and optimizing networks to ensure that they carry traffic with the speed, reliability, and capacity that is appropriate for the nature of the application and the cost constraints of the organization.
[src:vertical-pod-autoscaling/capacity-management] Different applications warrant different blends of capacity, latency, and reliability.
[src:vertical-pod-autoscaling/capacity-management] Network Performance management is a core component of the FCAPS ISO telecommunications framework (the 'P' stands for Performance in this acronym).
[src:vertical-pod-autoscaling/capacity-management] It enables the network engineers to proactively prepare for degradations in their IT infrastructure and ultimately help the end-user experience.
[src:vertical-pod-autoscaling/capacity-management] Network managers perform many tasks; these include performance measurement, forensic analysis, capacity planning, and load-testing or load generation.
[src:vertical-pod-autoscaling/capacity-management] They also work closely with application developers and IT departments who rely on them to deliver underlying network services.
[src:vertical-pod-autoscaling/capacity-management] Next-generation NPM tools are those that improve network management by automating the collection of network data, including capacity issues, and automatically interpreting it.
[src:vertical-pod-autoscaling/capacity-management] Terry Slattery, editor at NoJitter.com, compares three such tools, VMWare's vRealize Network Insight, PathSolutions TotalView, and Kemp Flowmon, in the article *The Future of Network Performance Management*, June 10, 2021.
[src:vertical-pod-autoscaling/capacity-management] New approaches to network management promise to help us detect and resolve network problems...
[src:vertical-pod-autoscaling/kubernetes] The name *Kubernetes* comes from the Ancient Greek term κυβερνήτης, *kubernḗtēs* (helmsman, pilot), which is also the origin of the words *cybernetics* and (through Latin) *governor*.
[src:vertical-pod-autoscaling/kubernetes] "Kubernetes" is often abbreviated with the numerical contraction "K8s", meaning "the letter K, followed by 8 letters, followed by s".
[src:vertical-pod-autoscaling/kubernetes] Kubernetes assembles one or more computers, either virtual machines or bare metal, into a cluster which can run workloads in containers.
[src:vertical-pod-autoscaling/kubernetes] It works with various container runtimes, such as containerd and CRI-O.
[src:vertical-pod-autoscaling/kubernetes] Its suitability for running and managing workloads of all sizes and styles has led to its widespread adoption in clouds and data centers.
[src:vertical-pod-autoscaling/kubernetes] There are multiple distributions of this platform—from independent software vendors (ISVs) as well as hosted-on-cloud offerings from all the major public cloud vendors.
[src:vertical-pod-autoscaling/kubernetes] The software consists of a control plane and nodes on which the actual applications run.
[src:vertical-pod-autoscaling/kubernetes] It includes tools like `kubeadm` and `kubectl` which can be used to interact with its REST-based API.
[src:vertical-pod-autoscaling/kubernetes] Kubernetes was announced by Google on June 6, 2014.
[src:vertical-pod-autoscaling/kubernetes] The project was conceived and created by Google employees Joe Beda, Brendan Burns, and Craig McLuckie.
[src:vertical-pod-autoscaling/kubernetes] Others at Google soon joined to help build the project including Ville Aikas, Dawn Chen, Brian Grant, Tim Hockin, and Daniel Smith.
[src:vertical-pod-autoscaling/kubernetes] Other companies such as Red Hat and CoreOS joined the effort soon after, with notable contributors such as Clayton Coleman and Kelsey Hightower.
[src:vertical-pod-autoscaling/kubernetes] The design and development of Kubernetes was inspired by Google's Borg cluster manager and based on Promise Theory.
[src:vertical-pod-autoscaling/kubernetes] Many of its top contributors had previously worked on Borg; they codenamed Kubernetes "Project 7" after the *Star Trek* ex-Borg character Seven of Nine and gave its logo a seven-spoked ship's wheel (designed by Tim Hockin).
[src:vertical-pod-autoscaling/kubernetes] Unlike Borg, which was written in C++, Kubernetes is written in the Go language.
[src:vertical-pod-autoscaling/kubernetes] Kubernetes was announced in June, 2014 and version 1.0 was released on July 21, 2015.
[src:vertical-pod-autoscaling/kubernetes] Google worked with the Linux Foundation to form the Cloud Native Computing Foundation (CNCF) and offered Kubernetes as the seed technology.
[src:vertical-pod-autoscaling/kubernetes] Google was already offering a managed Kubernetes service, GKE, and Red Hat was supporting Kubernetes as part of OpenShift since the inception of the Kubernetes project in 2014.
[src:vertical-pod-autoscaling/kubernetes] On March 6, 2018, Kubernetes Project reached ninth place in the list of GitHub projects by the number of commits, and second place in authors and issues, after the Linux kernel.
[src:vertical-pod-autoscaling/kubernetes] Until version 1.18, Kubernetes followed an N-2 support policy, meaning that the three most recent minor versions receive security updates and bug fixes.
[src:vertical-pod-autoscaling/kubernetes] Starting with version 1.19, Kubernetes follows an N-3 support policy.
[src:vertical-pod-autoscaling/kubernetes] Kubernetes defines a set of building blocks ("primitives") that collectively provide mechanisms that deploy, maintain, and scale applications based on CPU, memory or custom metrics.
[src:vertical-pod-autoscaling/kubernetes] Kubernetes is loosely coupled and extensible to meet the needs of different workloads.
[src:vertical-pod-autoscaling/kubernetes] The internal components as well as extensions and containers that run on Kubernetes rely on the Kubernetes API.
[src:vertical-pod-autoscaling/kubernetes] The platform exerts its control over compute and storage resources by defining resources as objects, which can then be managed as such.
[src:vertical-pod-autoscaling/kubernetes] Kubernetes follows the primary/replica architecture.
[src:vertical-pod-autoscaling/kubernetes] The components of Kubernetes can be divided into those that manage an individual node and those that are part of the control plane.
[src:vertical-pod-autoscaling/kubernetes] The Kubernetes master node handles the Kubernetes control plane of the cluster, managing its workload and directing communication across the system.
[src:vertical-pod-autoscaling/kubernetes] The Kubernetes control plane consists of various components such as TLS encryption, role-based access control (RBAC) and a strong authentication method, network separation, each its own process, that can run both on a single master node or on multiple masters supporting high-availability clusters.
[src:vertical-pod-autoscaling/kubernetes] The various components of the Kubernetes control plane are as follows.
[src:vertical-pod-autoscaling/kubernetes] Etcd is a persistent, lightweight, distributed, key-value data store (originally developed as part of CoreOS).
[src:vertical-pod-autoscaling/kubernetes] It reliably stores the configuration data of the cluster, representing the overall state of the cluster at any given point of time.
[src:vertical-pod-autoscaling/kubernetes] Etcd favors consistency over availability in the event of a network partition (see CAP theorem).
[src:vertical-pod-autoscaling/kubernetes] The consistency is crucial for correctly scheduling and operating services.
[src:vertical-pod-autoscaling/kubernetes] The API server serves the Kubernetes API using JSON over HTTP, which provides both the internal and external interface to Kubernetes.
[src:vertical-pod-autoscaling/kubernetes] The API server processes, validates REST requests, and updates the state of the API objects in etcd, thereby allowing clients to configure workloads and containers across worker nodes.
[src:vertical-pod-autoscaling/kubernetes] The API server uses etcd's watch API to monitor the cluster, roll out critical configuration changes, or restore any divergences of the state of the cluster back to the desired state as declared in etcd.
[src:vertical-pod-autoscaling/kubernetes] As an example, a human operator may specify that three instances of a particular "pod" (see below) need to be running, and etcd stores this fact.
[src:vertical-pod-autoscaling/kubernetes] If the Deployment controller finds that only two instances are running (conflicting with the etcd declaration), it schedules the creation of an additional instance of that pod.
[src:vertical-pod-autoscaling/kubernetes] The scheduler is an extensible component that selects the node that an unscheduled pod (the basic unit of workloads to be scheduled) runs on, based on resource availability and other constraints.
[src:vertical-pod-autoscaling/kubernetes] The scheduler tracks resource allocation on each node to ensure that workload is not scheduled in excess of available resources.
[src:vertical-pod-autoscaling/kubernetes] For this purpose, the scheduler must know the resource requirements, resource availability, and other user-provided constraints or policy directives such as quality-of-service, affinity/anti-affinity requirements, and data locality.
[src:vertical-pod-autoscaling/kubernetes] The scheduler's role is to match resource "supply" to workload "demand".
[src:vertical-pod-autoscaling/kubernetes] Kubernetes allows running multiple schedulers within a single cluster.
[src:vertical-pod-autoscaling/kubernetes] As such, scheduler plug-ins may be developed and installed as in-process extensions to the native vanilla scheduler by running it as a separate scheduler, as long as they conform to the Kubernetes scheduling framework.
[src:vertical-pod-autoscaling/kubernetes] This allows cluster administrators to extend or modify the behavior of the default Kubernetes scheduler according to their needs.
[src:vertical-pod-autoscaling/kubernetes] A controller is a reconciliation loop that drives the actual cluster state toward the desired state, communicating with the API server to create, update, and delete the resources it manages (e.g., pods or service endpoints).
[src:vertical-pod-autoscaling/kubernetes] An example controller is a ReplicaSet controller, which handles replication and scaling by running a specified number of copies of a pod across the cluster.
[src:vertical-pod-autoscaling/kubernetes] The controller also handles creating replacement pods if the underlying node fails.
[src:vertical-pod-autoscaling/kubernetes] Other controllers that are part of the core Kubernetes system include a DaemonSet controller for running exactly one pod on every machine (or some subset of machines), and a Job controller for running pods that run to completion (e.g. as part of a batch job).
[src:vertical-pod-autoscaling/kubernetes] Labels selectors often form part of the controller's definition that specify the set of pods that a controller manages.
[src:vertical-pod-autoscaling/kubernetes] The controller manager is a single process that manages several core Kubernetes controllers (including the examples described above), is distributed as part of the standard Kubernetes installation and responding to the loss of nodes.
[src:vertical-pod-autoscaling/kubernetes] Custom controllers may also be installed in the cluster, further allowing the behavior and API of Kubernetes to be extended when used in conjunction with custom resources (see custom resources, controllers and operators below).
[src:vertical-pod-autoscaling/kubernetes] A node, also known as a worker or a minion, is a machine where containers (workloads) are deployed.
[src:vertical-pod-autoscaling/kubernetes] Every node in the cluster must run a container runtime, as well as the below-mentioned components, for communication with the primary network configuration of these containers.
[src:vertical-pod-autoscaling/kubernetes] kubelet is responsible for the running state of each node, ensuring that all containers on the node are healthy.
[src:vertical-pod-autoscaling/kubernetes] It takes care of starting, stopping, and maintaining application containers organized into pods as directed by the control plane. kubelet monitors the state of a pod, and if not in the desired state, the pod re-deploys to the same node.
[src:vertical-pod-autoscaling/kubernetes] Node status is relayed every few seconds via heartbeat messages to the API server.
[src:vertical-pod-autoscaling/kubernetes] Once the control plane detects a node failure, a higher-level controller is expected to observe this state change and launch pods on another healthy node.
[src:vertical-pod-autoscaling/kubernetes] A container runtime is responsible for the lifecycle of containers, including launching, reconciling and killing of containers. kubelet interacts with container runtimes via the Container Runtime Interface (CRI), which decouples the maintenance of core Kubernetes from the actual CRI implementation.
[src:vertical-pod-autoscaling/kubernetes] Originally, kubelet interfaced exclusively with the Docker runtime through a "dockershim".
[src:vertical-pod-autoscaling/kubernetes] However, from November 2020 up to April 2022, Kubernetes has deprecated the shim in favor of directly interfacing with the container through containerd, or replacing Docker with a runtime that is compliant with the Container Runtime Interface (CRI).
[src:vertical-pod-autoscaling/kubernetes] With the release of v1.24 in May 2022, the "dockershim" has been removed entirely.
[src:vertical-pod-autoscaling/kubernetes] Examples of popular container runtimes that are compatible with kubelet include containerd (initially supported via Docker) and CRI-O.
[src:vertical-pod-autoscaling/kubernetes] kube-proxy is an implementation of a network proxy and a load balancer, and it supports the service abstraction along with the other networking operations.
[src:vertical-pod-autoscaling/kubernetes] It is responsible for routing traffic to the appropriate container based on IP and port number of the incoming request.
[src:vertical-pod-autoscaling/kubernetes] In Kubernetes, namespaces are utilized to segregate the resources it handles into distinct and non-intersecting collections.
[src:vertical-pod-autoscaling/kubernetes] They are intended for use in environments with many users spread across multiple teams, or projects, or even separating environments like development, test, and production.
[src:vertical-pod-autoscaling/kubernetes] The basic scheduling unit in Kubernetes is a pod, which consists of one or more containers that are guaranteed to be co-located on the same node.
[src:vertical-pod-autoscaling/kubernetes] Each pod in Kubernetes is assigned a unique IP address within the cluster, allowing applications to use ports without the risk of conflict.
[src:vertical-pod-autoscaling/kubernetes] Within the pod, all containers can reference each other.
[src:vertical-pod-autoscaling/kubernetes] The container is the lowest level of a micro-service, which holds the running application, libraries, and their dependencies.
[src:vertical-pod-autoscaling/kubernetes] Kubernetes supports several abstractions of workloads that are at a higher level over simple pods.
[src:vertical-pod-autoscaling/kubernetes] This allows users to declaratively define and manage these high-level abstractions, instead of having to manage individual pods by themselves.
[src:vertical-pod-autoscaling/kubernetes] Several of these abstractions, supported by a standard installation of Kubernetes, are described below.
[src:vertical-pod-autoscaling/kubernetes] A ReplicaSet's purpose is to maintain a stable set of replica pods running at any given time.
[src:vertical-pod-autoscaling/kubernetes] As such, it is often used to guarantee the availability of a specified number of identical Pods.
[src:vertical-pod-autoscaling/kubernetes] The ReplicaSet can also be said to be a grouping mechanism that lets Kubernetes maintain the number of instances that have been declared for a given pod.
[src:vertical-pod-autoscaling/kubernetes] The definition of a ReplicaSet uses a selector, whose evaluation will result in identifying all pods that are associated with it.
[src:vertical-pod-autoscaling/kubernetes] A ReplicationController, similar to a ReplicaSet, serves the same purpose and behaves similarly to a ReplicaSet, which is to ensure that there will always be a specified number of pod replicas as desired.
[src:vertical-pod-autoscaling/kubernetes] The ReplicationController workload was the predecessor of a ReplicaSet, but was eventually deprecated in favor of ReplicaSet to make use of set-based label selectors.
[src:vertical-pod-autoscaling/kubernetes] Deployments are a higher-level management mechanism for ReplicaSets.
[src:vertical-pod-autoscaling/kubernetes] While the ReplicaSet controller manages the scale of the ReplicaSet, the Deployment controller manages what happens to the ReplicaSet – whether an update has to be rolled out, or rolled back, etc.
[src:vertical-pod-autoscaling/kubernetes] When Deployments are scaled up or down, this results in the declaration of the ReplicaSet changing, and this change in the declared state is managed by the ReplicaSet controller.
[src:vertical-pod-autoscaling/kubernetes] StatefulSets are controllers that enforce the properties of uniqueness and ordering amongst instances of a pod, and can be used to run stateful applications.
[src:vertical-pod-autoscaling/kubernetes] While scaling stateless applications is only a matter of adding more running pods, doing so for stateful workloads is harder, because the state needs to be preserved if a pod is restarted.
[src:vertical-pod-autoscaling/kubernetes] If the application is scaled up or down, the state may need to be redistributed.
[src:vertical-pod-autoscaling/kubernetes] Databases are an example of stateful workloads.
[src:vertical-pod-autoscaling/kubernetes] When run in high-availability mode, many databases come with the notion of a primary instance and secondary instances.
[src:vertical-pod-autoscaling/kubernetes] In this case, the notion of ordering of instances is important.
[src:vertical-pod-autoscaling/kubernetes] Other applications like Apache Kafka distribute the data amongst their brokers; hence, one broker is not the same as another.
[src:vertical-pod-autoscaling/kubernetes] In this case, the notion of instance uniqueness is important.
[src:vertical-pod-autoscaling/kubernetes] DaemonSets are responsible for ensuring that a pod is created on every single node in the cluster.
[src:vertical-pod-autoscaling/kubernetes] Generally, most workloads scale in response to a desired replica count, depending on the availability and performance requirements as needed by the application.
[src:vertical-pod-autoscaling/kubernetes] However, in other scenarios it may be necessary to deploy a pod to every single node in the cluster, scaling up the number of total pods as nodes are added and garbage collecting them as they are removed.
[src:vertical-pod-autoscaling/kubernetes] This is particularly helpful for use cases where the workload has some dependency on the actual node or host machine, such as log collection, ingress controllers, and storage services.
[src:vertical-pod-autoscaling/kubernetes] A Kubernetes service is a set of pods that work together, such as one tier of a multi-tier application.
[src:vertical-pod-autoscaling/kubernetes] The set of pods that constitute a service are defined by a label selector.
[src:vertical-pod-autoscaling/kubernetes] Kubernetes provides two modes of service discovery, using environment variables or using Kubernetes DNS.
[src:vertical-pod-autoscaling/kubernetes] Service discovery assigns a stable IP address and DNS name to the service, and load balances traffic in a round-robin manner to network connections of that IP address among the pods matching the selector (even as failures cause the pods to move from machine to machine).
[src:vertical-pod-autoscaling/kubernetes] By default a service is exposed inside a cluster (e.g., back end pods might be grouped into a service, with requests from the front-end pods load-balanced among them), but a service can also be exposed outside a cluster (e.g., for clients to reach front-end pods).
[src:vertical-pod-autoscaling/kubernetes] Filesystems in the Kubernetes container provide ephemeral storage, by default.
[src:vertical-pod-autoscaling/kubernetes] This means that a restart of the pod will wipe out any data on such containers, and therefore, this form of storage is quite limiting in anything but trivial applications.
[src:vertical-pod-autoscaling/kubernetes] A Kubernetes volume provides persistent storage that exists for the lifetime of the pod itself.
[src:vertical-pod-autoscaling/kubernetes] This storage can also be used as shared disk space for containers within the pod.
[src:vertical-pod-autoscaling/kubernetes] Volumes are mounted at specific mount points within the container, which are defined by the pod configuration, and cannot mount onto other volumes or link to other volumes.
[src:vertical-pod-autoscaling/kubernetes] The same volume can be mounted at different points in the file system tree by different containers.
[src:vertical-pod-autoscaling/kubernetes] A common application challenge is deciding where to store and manage configuration information, some of which may contain sensitive data.
[src:vertical-pod-autoscaling/kubernetes] Configuration data can be anything as fine-grained as individual properties, or coarse-grained information like entire configuration files such as JSON or XML documents.
[src:vertical-pod-autoscaling/kubernetes] Kubernetes provides two closely related mechanisms to deal with this need, known as ConfigMaps and Secrets, both of which allow for configuration changes to be made without requiring an application rebuild.
[src:vertical-pod-autoscaling/kubernetes] The data from ConfigMaps and Secrets will be made available to every single instance of the application to which these objects have been bound via the Deployment.
[src:vertical-pod-autoscaling/kubernetes] A Secret and/or a ConfigMap is sent to a node only if a pod on that node requires it, which will only be stored in memory on the node.
[src:vertical-pod-autoscaling/kubernetes] Once the pod that depends on the Secret or ConfigMap is deleted, the in-memory copy of all bound Secrets and ConfigMaps are deleted as well.
[src:vertical-pod-autoscaling/kubernetes] Mounted within a volume accessible within the container's filesystem, which supports automatic reloading without restarting the container.
[src:vertical-pod-autoscaling/kubernetes] The biggest difference between a Secret and a ConfigMap is that Secrets are specifically designed for containing secure and confidential data, although they are not encrypted at rest by default, and requires additional setup in order to fully secure the use of Secrets within the cluster.
[src:vertical-pod-autoscaling/kubernetes] Secrets are often used to store confidential or sensitive data like certificates, credentials to work with image registries, passwords, and ssh keys.
[src:vertical-pod-autoscaling/kubernetes] Kubernetes enables clients (users or internal components) to attach keys called labels to any API object in the system, such as pods and nodes.
[src:vertical-pod-autoscaling/kubernetes] Correspondingly, label selectors are queries against labels that resolve to matching objects.
[src:vertical-pod-autoscaling/kubernetes] When a service is defined, one can define the label selectors that will be used by the service router/load balancer to select the pod instances that the traffic will be routed to.
[src:vertical-pod-autoscaling/kubernetes] Thus, simply changing the labels of the pods or changing the label selectors on the service can be used to control which pods get traffic and which don't, which can be used to support various deployment patterns like blue–green deployments or A/B testing.
[src:vertical-pod-autoscaling/kubernetes] This capability to dynamically control how services utilize implementing resources provides a loose coupling within the infrastructure.
[src:vertical-pod-autoscaling/kubernetes] Just like labels, field selectors also let one select Kubernetes resources.
[src:vertical-pod-autoscaling/kubernetes] Unlike labels, the selection is based on the attribute values inherent to the resource being selected, rather than user-defined categorization.
[src:vertical-pod-autoscaling/kubernetes] `metadata.name` and `metadata.namespace` are field selectors that will be present on all Kubernetes objects.
[src:vertical-pod-autoscaling/kubernetes] Other selectors that can be used depend on the object/resource type.
[src:vertical-pod-autoscaling/kubernetes] Add-ons are additional features of the Kubernetes cluster implemented as applications running within it.
[src:vertical-pod-autoscaling/kubernetes] The pods may be managed by Deployments, ReplicationControllers, and so on.
[src:vertical-pod-autoscaling/kubernetes] Cluster DNS is a DNS server, in addition to the other DNS server(s) in the environment, which serves DNS records for Kubernetes services.
[src:vertical-pod-autoscaling/kubernetes] Containers started by Kubernetes automatically include this DNS server in their DNS searches.
[src:vertical-pod-autoscaling/kubernetes] This is a general purpose, web-based UI for Kubernetes clusters.
[src:vertical-pod-autoscaling/kubernetes] It allows administrators to manage and troubleshoot applications running in the cluster, as well as the cluster itself.
[src:vertical-pod-autoscaling/kubernetes] Container Resource Monitoring records metrics about containers in a central database, and provides a UI for browsing that data.
[src:vertical-pod-autoscaling/kubernetes] Kubernetes cost monitoring applications allow breakdown of costs by pods, nodes, namespaces, and labels.
