[src:vertical-pod-autoscaling/kubernetes] Containers emerged as a way to make software portable.
[src:vertical-pod-autoscaling/kubernetes] The container contains all the packages needed to run a service.
[src:vertical-pod-autoscaling/kubernetes] The provided file system makes containers extremely portable and easy to use in development.
[src:vertical-pod-autoscaling/kubernetes] A container can be moved from development to test or production with no or relatively few configuration changes.
[src:vertical-pod-autoscaling/kubernetes] Historically Kubernetes was suitable only for stateless services.
[src:vertical-pod-autoscaling/kubernetes] However, many applications have a database, which requires persistence, leading to the creation of persistent storage for Kubernetes.
[src:vertical-pod-autoscaling/kubernetes] Implementing persistent storage for containers is one of the top challenges of Kubernetes administrators, DevOps and cloud engineers.
[src:vertical-pod-autoscaling/kubernetes] Containers may be ephemeral, but more and more of their data is not, so one needs to ensure the data's survival in case of container termination or hardware failure.
[src:vertical-pod-autoscaling/kubernetes] When deploying containers with Kubernetes or containerized applications, organizations often realize that they need persistent storage.
[src:vertical-pod-autoscaling/kubernetes] They need to provide fast and reliable storage for databases, root images and other data used by the containers.
[src:vertical-pod-autoscaling/kubernetes] In addition to the landscape, the Cloud Native Computing Foundation (CNCF), has published other information about Kubernetes Persistent Storage including a blog helping to define the container attached storage pattern.
[src:vertical-pod-autoscaling/kubernetes] This pattern can be thought of as one that uses Kubernetes itself as a component of the storage system or service.
[src:vertical-pod-autoscaling/kubernetes] Container Attached Storage is a type of data storage that emerged as Kubernetes gained prominence.
[src:vertical-pod-autoscaling/kubernetes] The Container Attached Storage approach or pattern relies on Kubernetes itself for certain capabilities while delivering primarily block, file, object and interfaces to workloads running on Kubernetes.
[src:vertical-pod-autoscaling/kubernetes] Common attributes of Container Attached Storage include the use of extensions to Kubernetes, such as custom resource definitions, and the use of Kubernetes itself for functions that otherwise would be separately developed and deployed for storage or data management.
[src:vertical-pod-autoscaling/kubernetes] Examples of functionality delivered by custom resource definitions or by Kubernetes itself include retry logic, delivered by Kubernetes itself, and the creation and maintenance of an inventory of available storage media and volumes, typically delivered via a custom resource definition.
[src:vertical-pod-autoscaling/kubernetes] In Kubernetes version 1.9, the initial Alpha release of Container Storage Interface (CSI) was introduced.
[src:vertical-pod-autoscaling/kubernetes] Previously, storage volume plug-ins were included in the Kubernetes distribution.
[src:vertical-pod-autoscaling/kubernetes] By creating a standardized CSI, the code required to interface with external storage systems was separated from the core Kubernetes code base.
[src:vertical-pod-autoscaling/kubernetes] Just one year later, the CSI feature was made Generally Available (GA) in Kubernetes.
[src:vertical-pod-autoscaling/kubernetes] A key component of the Kubernetes control plane is the API Server, which exposes an HTTP API that can be invoked by other parts of the cluster as well as end users and external components.
[src:vertical-pod-autoscaling/kubernetes] This API is a REST API and is declarative in nature, and is the same API exposed to the control plane.
[src:vertical-pod-autoscaling/kubernetes] The API server is backed by etcd to store all records persistently.
[src:vertical-pod-autoscaling/kubernetes] In Kubernetes, all objects serve as the "record of intent" of the cluster's state, and are able to define the desired state that the writer of the object wishes for the cluster to be in.
[src:vertical-pod-autoscaling/kubernetes] All objects in Kubernetes are subject to the same API conventions.
[src:vertical-pod-autoscaling/kubernetes] The Kubernetes API can be extended using *Custom Resources*, which represent objects that are not part of the standard Kubernetes installation.
[src:vertical-pod-autoscaling/kubernetes] These custom resources are declared using *Custom Resource Definitions* (CRDs), which is a kind of resource that can be dynamically registered and unregistered without shutting down or restarting a cluster that is currently running.
[src:vertical-pod-autoscaling/kubernetes] Custom controllers are another extension mechanism that interact with the Kubernetes API, similar to the default controllers in the standard pre-installed Kubernetes controller manager.
[src:vertical-pod-autoscaling/kubernetes] These controllers may interact with custom resources to allow for a declarative API: users may declare the desired state of the system via the custom resources, and it is the responsibility of the custom controller to observe the change and reconcile it.
[src:vertical-pod-autoscaling/kubernetes] The combination of custom resources and custom controllers are often referred to as a *Kubernetes* *Operator*.
[src:vertical-pod-autoscaling/kubernetes] The key use case for operators are to capture the aim of a human operator who is managing a service or set of services and to implement them using automation, and with a declarative API supporting this automation.
[src:vertical-pod-autoscaling/kubernetes] Human operators who look after specific applications and services have deep knowledge of how the system ought to behave, how to deploy it, and how to react if there are problems.
[src:vertical-pod-autoscaling/kubernetes] Examples of problems solved by operators include taking and restoring backups of that application's state, and handling upgrades of the application code alongside related changes such as database schemas or extra configuration settings.
[src:vertical-pod-autoscaling/kubernetes] Several notable projects under the Cloud Native Computing Foundation's incubation program follow the operator pattern to extend Kubernetes, including Argo, Open Policy Agent and Istio.
[src:vertical-pod-autoscaling/kubernetes] Kubernetes defines the following strategies for controlling access to its API.
[src:vertical-pod-autoscaling/kubernetes] The Kubernetes API server listens on a TCP port that serves HTTPS traffic, in order to enforce transport layer security (TLS) using CA certificates.
[src:vertical-pod-autoscaling/kubernetes] In older versions of Kubernetes, the API server supported listening on both HTTP and HTTPS ports (with the HTTP port number having no transport security whatsoever).
[src:vertical-pod-autoscaling/kubernetes] This was deprecated in v1.10 and eventually dropped support in v1.20 of Kubernetes.
[src:vertical-pod-autoscaling/kubernetes] Users are typically expected to indicate and define cluster URL details along with the necessary credentials in a *kubeconfig* file, which are natively supported by other Kubernetes tools like kubectl and the official Kubernetes client libraries.
[src:vertical-pod-autoscaling/kubernetes] *Attribute-based access control (ABAC) mode*: Grants access rights to users through the use of defined access control policies which combine attributes together.
[src:vertical-pod-autoscaling/kubernetes] *Role-based access control (RBAC) mode*: Grants access rights to users based on roles that are granted to the user, where each role defines a list of actions that are allowed.
[src:vertical-pod-autoscaling/kubernetes] *Webhook mode*: Queries a REST API service to determine if a user is authorized to perform a given action.
[src:vertical-pod-autoscaling/kubernetes] The same API design principles have been used to define an API to harness a program in order to create, configure, and manage Kubernetes clusters.
[src:vertical-pod-autoscaling/kubernetes] A key concept embodied in the API is using Infrastructure as Software, or the notion that the Kubernetes cluster infrastructure is itself a resource / object that can be managed just like any other Kubernetes resources.
[src:vertical-pod-autoscaling/kubernetes] Similarly, machines that make up the cluster are also treated as a Kubernetes resource.
[src:vertical-pod-autoscaling/kubernetes] The API has two pieces – the core API, and a provider implementation.
