[src:vertical-pod-autoscaling/memory-management] Several methods have been devised that increase the effectiveness of memory management.
[src:vertical-pod-autoscaling/memory-management] Virtual memory systems separate the memory addresses used by a process from actual physical addresses, allowing separation of processes and increasing the size of the virtual address space beyond the available amount of RAM using paging or swapping to secondary storage.
[src:vertical-pod-autoscaling/memory-management] The quality of the virtual memory manager can have an extensive effect on overall system performance.
[src:vertical-pod-autoscaling/memory-management] The system allows a computer to appear as if it may have more memory available than physically present, thereby allowing multiple processes to share it.
[src:vertical-pod-autoscaling/memory-management] Burroughs/Unisys MCP, and OS/360 and successors, memory is managed by the operating system.
[src:vertical-pod-autoscaling/memory-management] Unix-like operating systems, memory is managed at the application level.
[src:vertical-pod-autoscaling/memory-management] Memory management within an address space is generally categorized as either manual memory management or automatic memory management.
[src:vertical-pod-autoscaling/memory-management] The task of fulfilling an allocation request consists of locating a block of unused memory of sufficient size.
[src:vertical-pod-autoscaling/memory-management] Memory requests are satisfied by allocating portions from a large pool of memory called the *heap* or *free store*.
[src:vertical-pod-autoscaling/memory-management] At any given time, some parts of the heap are in use, while some are "free" (unused) and thus available for future allocations.
[src:vertical-pod-autoscaling/memory-management] In the C language, the function which allocates memory from the heap is called `malloc` and the function which takes previously allocated memory and marks it as "free" (to be used by future allocations) is called `free`.
[src:vertical-pod-autoscaling/memory-management] Several issues complicate the implementation, such as external fragmentation, which arises when there are many small gaps between allocated memory blocks, which invalidates their use for an allocation request.
[src:vertical-pod-autoscaling/memory-management] The allocator's metadata can also inflate the size of (individually) small allocations.
[src:vertical-pod-autoscaling/memory-management] The memory management system must track outstanding allocations to ensure that they do not overlap and that no memory is ever "lost" (i.e. that there are no "memory leaks").
[src:vertical-pod-autoscaling/memory-management] The specific dynamic memory allocation algorithm implemented can impact performance significantly.
[src:vertical-pod-autoscaling/memory-management] A study conducted in 1994 by Digital Equipment Corporation illustrates the overheads involved for a variety of allocators.
[src:vertical-pod-autoscaling/memory-management] The lowest average instruction path length required to allocate a single memory slot was 52 (as measured with an instruction level profiler on a variety of software).
[src:vertical-pod-autoscaling/memory-management] Since the precise location of the allocation is not known in advance, the memory is accessed indirectly, usually through a pointer reference.
[src:vertical-pod-autoscaling/memory-management] Fixed-size blocks allocation, also called memory pool allocation, uses a free list of fixed-size blocks of memory (often all of the same size).
[src:vertical-pod-autoscaling/memory-management] This works well for simple embedded systems where no large objects need to be allocated but suffers from fragmentation especially with long memory addresses.
[src:vertical-pod-autoscaling/memory-management] However, due to the significantly reduced overhead, this method can substantially improve performance for objects that need frequent allocation and deallocation, and so it is often used in video games.
[src:vertical-pod-autoscaling/memory-management] In this system, memory is allocated into several pools of memory instead of just one, where each pool represents blocks of memory of a certain power of two in size, or blocks of some other convenient size progression.
[src:vertical-pod-autoscaling/memory-management] All blocks of a particular size are kept in a sorted linked list or tree and all new blocks that are formed during allocation are added to their respective memory pools for later use.
[src:vertical-pod-autoscaling/memory-management] If a smaller size is requested than is available, the smallest available size is selected and split.
[src:vertical-pod-autoscaling/memory-management] When a block is split, it is divided into two smaller blocks, and each smaller block becomes a unique "buddy" to the other.
[src:vertical-pod-autoscaling/memory-management] One of the resulting parts is selected, and the process repeats until the request is complete.
[src:vertical-pod-autoscaling/memory-management] When a block is allocated, the allocator will start with the smallest sufficiently large block to avoid needlessly breaking blocks.
[src:vertical-pod-autoscaling/memory-management] When a block is freed, it is compared to its buddy.
[src:vertical-pod-autoscaling/memory-management] If they are both free, they are combined and placed in the correspondingly larger-sized buddy-block list.
[src:vertical-pod-autoscaling/memory-management] This memory allocation mechanism preallocates memory chunks suitable to fit objects of a certain type or size.
[src:vertical-pod-autoscaling/memory-management] These chunks are called caches and the allocator only has to keep track of a list of free cache slots.
[src:vertical-pod-autoscaling/memory-management] Constructing an object will use any one of the free cache slots and destructing an object will add a slot back to the free cache slot list.
[src:vertical-pod-autoscaling/memory-management] This technique alleviates memory fragmentation and is efficient as there is no need to search for a suitable portion of memory, as any open slot will suffice.
[src:vertical-pod-autoscaling/memory-management] Many Unix-like systems as well as Microsoft Windows implement a function called `alloca` for dynamically allocating stack memory in a way similar to the heap-based `malloc`.
[src:vertical-pod-autoscaling/memory-management] A compiler typically translates it to inlined instructions manipulating the stack pointer.
[src:vertical-pod-autoscaling/memory-management] Although there is no need of manually freeing memory allocated this way, as it is automatically freed when the function that called `alloca` returns, there exists a risk of overflow.
[src:vertical-pod-autoscaling/memory-management] And since alloca is an *ad hoc* expansion seen in many systems but never in POSIX or the C standard, its behavior in case of a stack overflow is undefined.
[src:vertical-pod-autoscaling/memory-management] A safer version of alloca called `_malloca`, which reports errors, exists on Microsoft Windows.
[src:vertical-pod-autoscaling/memory-management] It requires the use of `_freea`. gnulib provides an equivalent interface, albeit instead of throwing an SEH exception on overflow, it delegates to malloc when an overlarge size is detected.
[src:vertical-pod-autoscaling/memory-management] A similar feature can be emulated using manual accounting and size-checking, such as in the uses of `alloca_account` in glibc.
[src:vertical-pod-autoscaling/memory-management] The proper management of memory in an application is a difficult problem, and several different strategies for handling memory management have been devised.
[src:vertical-pod-autoscaling/memory-management] Special declarations may allow local variables to retain values between invocations of the procedure, or may allow local variables to be accessed by other subroutines.
[src:vertical-pod-autoscaling/memory-management] The automatic allocation of local variables makes recursion possible, to a depth limited by available memory.
[src:vertical-pod-autoscaling/memory-management] Garbage collection is a strategy for automatically detecting memory allocated to objects that are no longer usable in a program, and returning that allocated memory to a pool of free memory locations.
[src:vertical-pod-autoscaling/memory-management] This method is in contrast to "manual" memory management where a programmer explicitly codes memory requests and memory releases in the program.
[src:vertical-pod-autoscaling/memory-management] While automatic garbage collection has the advantages of reducing programmer workload and preventing certain kinds of memory allocation bugs, garbage collection does require memory resources of its own, and can compete with the application program for processor time.
[src:vertical-pod-autoscaling/memory-management] Reference counting is a strategy for detecting that memory is no longer usable by a program by maintaining a counter for how many independent pointers point to the memory.
[src:vertical-pod-autoscaling/memory-management] Whenever a new pointer points to a piece of memory, the programmer is supposed to increase the counter.
[src:vertical-pod-autoscaling/memory-management] When the pointer changes where it points, or when the pointer is no longer pointing to any area or has itself been freed, the counter should decrease.
[src:vertical-pod-autoscaling/memory-management] When the counter drops to zero, the memory should be considered unused and freed.
[src:vertical-pod-autoscaling/memory-management] Some reference counting systems require programmer involvement and some are implemented automatically by the compiler.
[src:vertical-pod-autoscaling/memory-management] A disadvantage of reference counting is that circular references can develop which cause a memory leak to occur.
[src:vertical-pod-autoscaling/memory-management] This can be mitigated by either adding the concept of a "weak reference" (a reference that does not participate in reference counting, but is notified when the area it is pointing to is no longer valid) or by combining reference counting and garbage collection together.
[src:vertical-pod-autoscaling/memory-management] A memory pool is a technique of automatically deallocating memory based on the state of the application, such as the lifecycle of a request or transaction.
[src:vertical-pod-autoscaling/memory-management] The idea is that many applications execute large chunks of code which may generate memory allocations, but that there is a point in execution where all of those chunks are known to be no longer valid.
[src:vertical-pod-autoscaling/memory-management] For example, in a web service, after each request the web service no longer needs any of the memory allocated during the execution of the request.
[src:vertical-pod-autoscaling/memory-management] Therefore, rather than keeping track of whether or not memory is currently being referenced, the memory is allocated according to the request or lifecycle stage with which it is associated.
[src:vertical-pod-autoscaling/memory-management] When that request or stage has passed, all associated memory is deallocated simultaneously.
[src:vertical-pod-autoscaling/memory-management] Virtual memory is a method of decoupling the memory organization from the physical hardware.
[src:vertical-pod-autoscaling/memory-management] The applications operate on memory via *virtual addresses*.
[src:vertical-pod-autoscaling/memory-management] Each attempt by the application to access a particular virtual memory address results in the virtual memory address being translated to an actual *physical address*.
[src:vertical-pod-autoscaling/memory-management] In this way the addition of virtual memory enables granular control over memory systems and methods of access.
[src:vertical-pod-autoscaling/memory-management] In virtual memory systems the operating system limits how a process can access the memory.
[src:vertical-pod-autoscaling/memory-management] This feature, called memory protection, can be used to disallow a process to read or write to memory that is not allocated to it, preventing malicious or malfunctioning code in one program from interfering with the operation of another.
[src:vertical-pod-autoscaling/memory-management] Even though the memory allocated for specific processes is normally isolated, processes sometimes need to be able to share information.
[src:vertical-pod-autoscaling/memory-management] Shared memory is one of the fastest techniques for inter-process communication.
[src:vertical-pod-autoscaling/memory-management] Memory is usually classified by access rate into primary storage and secondary storage.
[src:vertical-pod-autoscaling/memory-management] Memory management systems, among other operations, also handle the moving of information between these two levels of memory.
[src:vertical-pod-autoscaling/memory-management] An operating system manages various resources in the computing system.
[src:vertical-pod-autoscaling/memory-management] The memory subsystem is the system element for managing memory.
[src:vertical-pod-autoscaling/memory-management] The memory subsystem combines the hardware memory resource and the MCP OS software that manages the resource.
[src:vertical-pod-autoscaling/memory-management] The memory subsystem manages the physical memory and the virtual memory of the system (both part of the hardware resource).
[src:vertical-pod-autoscaling/memory-management] The virtual memory extends physical memory by using extra space on a peripheral device, usually disk.
[src:vertical-pod-autoscaling/memory-management] The memory subsystem is responsible for moving code and data between main and virtual memory in a process known as overlaying.
[src:vertical-pod-autoscaling/memory-management] Burroughs was the first commercial implementation of virtual memory (although developed at Manchester University for the Ferranti Atlas computer) and integrated virtual memory with the system design of the B5000 from the start (in 1961) needing no external memory management unit (MMU).
[src:vertical-pod-autoscaling/memory-management] The memory subsystem is responsible for mapping logical requests for memory blocks to physical portions of memory (segments) which are found in the list of free segments.
[src:vertical-pod-autoscaling/memory-management] Descriptors are essential in providing memory safety and security so that operations cannot overflow or underflow the referenced block (commonly known as buffer overflow).
[src:vertical-pod-autoscaling/memory-management] Descriptors themselves are protected control words that cannot be manipulated except for specific elements of the MCP OS (enabled by the UNSAFE block directive in NEWP).
[src:vertical-pod-autoscaling/memory-management] Donald Knuth describes a similar system in Section 2.5 ‘Dynamic Storage Allocation’ of ‘Fundamental Algorithms’.
[src:vertical-pod-autoscaling/memory-management] IBM System/360 does not support virtual memory.
[src:vertical-pod-autoscaling/memory-management] Memory isolation of jobs is optionally accomplished using protection keys, assigning storage for each job a different key, 0 for the supervisor or 1–15.
[src:vertical-pod-autoscaling/memory-management] Memory management in OS/360 is a supervisor function.
[src:vertical-pod-autoscaling/memory-management] Storage is requested using the `GETMAIN` macro and freed using the `FREEMAIN` macro, which result in a call to the supervisor (SVC) to perform the operation.
[src:vertical-pod-autoscaling/memory-management] In OS/360 the details vary depending on how the system is generated, e.g., for PCP, MFT, MVT.
[src:vertical-pod-autoscaling/memory-management] In OS/360 MVT, suballocation within a job's *region* or the shared *System Queue Area* (SQA) is based on *subpools*, areas a multiple of 2 KB in size—the size of an area protected by a protection key.
[src:vertical-pod-autoscaling/memory-management] Within a region subpools are assigned either the job's storage protection or the supervisor's key, key 0.
[src:vertical-pod-autoscaling/memory-management] Initially only subpool zero is created, and all user storage requests are satisfied from subpool 0, unless another is specified in the memory request.
[src:vertical-pod-autoscaling/memory-management] Subpools 250–255 are created by memory requests by the supervisor on behalf of the job.
[src:vertical-pod-autoscaling/memory-management] Most of these are assigned key 0, although a few get the key of the job.
[src:vertical-pod-autoscaling/memory-management] Subpool numbers are also relevant in MFT, although the details are much simpler.
[src:vertical-pod-autoscaling/memory-management] MFT uses fixed *partitions* redefinable by the operator instead of dynamic regions and PCP has only a single partition.
[src:vertical-pod-autoscaling/memory-management] Each subpool is mapped by a list of control blocks identifying allocated and free memory blocks within the subpool.
[src:vertical-pod-autoscaling/memory-management] Memory is allocated by finding a free area of sufficient size, or by allocating additional blocks in the subpool, up to the region size of the job.
[src:vertical-pod-autoscaling/memory-management] It is possible to free all or part of an allocated memory area.
[src:vertical-pod-autoscaling/memory-management] The details for OS/VS1 are similar to those for MFT and for MVT; the details for OS/VS2 are similar to those for MVT, except that the page size is 4 KiB.
[src:vertical-pod-autoscaling/memory-management] For both OS/VS1 and OS/VS2 the shared *System Queue Area* (SQA) is nonpageable.
[src:vertical-pod-autoscaling/memory-management] In MVS the address space includes an additional pageable shared area, the *Common Storage Area* (CSA), and two additional private areas, the nonpageable *local system queue area* (LSQA) and the pageable *System Work area* (SWA).
[src:vertical-pod-autoscaling/memory-management] Also, the storage keys 0–7 are all reserved for use by privileged code.
[src:vertical-pod-autoscaling/resource-management-computing] In computer programming, **resource management** refers to techniques for managing resources (components with limited availability).
[src:vertical-pod-autoscaling/resource-management-computing] Computer programs may manage their own resources by using features exposed by programming languages (Elder, Jackson & Liblit (2008) is a survey article contrasting different approaches), or may elect to manage them by a host – an operating system or virtual machine – or another program.
[src:vertical-pod-autoscaling/resource-management-computing] Host-based management is known as *resource tracking,* and consists of cleaning up resource leaks: terminating access to resources that have been acquired but not released after use.
[src:vertical-pod-autoscaling/resource-management-computing] This is known as *reclaiming* resources, and is analogous to garbage collection for memory.
[src:vertical-pod-autoscaling/resource-management-computing] On many systems, the operating system reclaims resources after the process makes the exit system call.
[src:vertical-pod-autoscaling/resource-management-computing] The omission of releasing a resource when a program has finished using it is known as a resource leak, and is an issue in sequential computing.
[src:vertical-pod-autoscaling/resource-management-computing] Multiple processes wish to access a limited resource can be an issue in concurrent computing, and is known as resource contention.
[src:vertical-pod-autoscaling/resource-management-computing] Resource management seeks to control access in order to prevent both of these situations.
[src:vertical-pod-autoscaling/resource-management-computing] Formally, resource management (preventing resource leaks) consists of ensuring that a resource is released if and only if it is successfully acquired.
[src:vertical-pod-autoscaling/resource-management-computing] This general problem can be abstracted as "*before,* *body,* and *after*" code, which normally are executed in this order, with the condition that the *after* code is called if and only if the *before* code successfully completes, regardless of whether the *body* code executes successfully or not.
[src:vertical-pod-autoscaling/resource-management-computing] This is also known as *execute around* or a *code sandwich,* and occurs in various other contexts, such as a temporary change of program state, or tracing entry and exit into a subroutine.
[src:vertical-pod-autoscaling/resource-management-computing] However, resource management is the most commonly cited application.
[src:vertical-pod-autoscaling/resource-management-computing] In aspect-oriented programming, such execute around logic is a form of *advice*.
[src:vertical-pod-autoscaling/resource-management-computing] In the terminology of control flow analysis, resource release must postdominate successful resource acquisition; failure to ensure this is a bug, and a code path that violates this condition causes a resource leak.
[src:vertical-pod-autoscaling/resource-management-computing] Resource leaks are often minor problems, generally not crashing the program, but instead causing some slowdown to the program or the overall system.
[src:vertical-pod-autoscaling/resource-management-computing] However, they may cause crashes – either the program itself or other programs – due to *resource exhaustion:* if the system runs out of resources, acquisition requests fail.
[src:vertical-pod-autoscaling/resource-management-computing] This can present a security bug if an attack can cause resource exhaustion.
[src:vertical-pod-autoscaling/resource-management-computing] Resource leaks may happen under regular program flow – such as simply forgetting to release a resource – or only in exceptional circumstances, such as when a resource is not released if there is an exception in another part of the program.
[src:vertical-pod-autoscaling/resource-management-computing] Resource leaks are very frequently caused by early exit from a subroutine, either by a `return` statement, or an exception raised either by the subroutine itself, or a deeper subroutine that it calls.
[src:vertical-pod-autoscaling/resource-management-computing] While resource release due to return statements can be handled by carefully releasing within the subroutine before the return, exceptions cannot be handled without some additional language facility that guarantees that release code is executed.
[src:vertical-pod-autoscaling/resource-management-computing] More subtly, successful resource acquisition must dominate resource release, as otherwise the code will try to release a resource it has not acquired.
[src:vertical-pod-autoscaling/resource-management-computing] The consequences of such an incorrect release range from being silently ignored to crashing the program or unpredictable behavior.
[src:vertical-pod-autoscaling/resource-management-computing] These bugs generally manifest rarely, as they require resource allocation to first fail, which is generally an exceptional case.
[src:vertical-pod-autoscaling/resource-management-computing] Further, the consequences may not be serious, as the program may already be crashing due to failure to acquire an essential resource.
[src:vertical-pod-autoscaling/resource-management-computing] However, these can prevent recovery from the failure, or turn an orderly shutdown into a disorderly shutdown.
[src:vertical-pod-autoscaling/resource-management-computing] In computer science, resource contention refers to a conflict that arises when multiple entities attempt to access a shared resource, like random access memory, disk storage, cache memory, internal buses, or external network devices.
[src:vertical-pod-autoscaling/resource-management-computing] Memory can be treated as a resource, but memory management is usually considered separately, primarily because memory allocation and deallocation is significantly more frequent than acquisition and release of other resources, such as file handles.
[src:vertical-pod-autoscaling/resource-management-computing] Memory managed by an *external* system has similarities to both (internal) memory management (since it is memory) and resource management (since it is managed by an external system).
[src:vertical-pod-autoscaling/resource-management-computing] Examples include memory managed via native code and used from Java (via Java Native Interface); and objects in the Document Object Model (DOM), used from JavaScript.
[src:vertical-pod-autoscaling/resource-management-computing] In both these cases, the memory manager (garbage collector) of the runtime environment (virtual machine) is unable to manage the external memory (there is no shared memory management), and thus the external memory is treated as a resource, and managed analogously.
[src:vertical-pod-autoscaling/resource-management-computing] However, cycles between systems (JavaScript referring to the DOM, referring back to JavaScript) can make management difficult or impossible.
[src:vertical-pod-autoscaling/resource-management-computing] Lexical management, when applicable, allows a better separation of concerns and is less error-prone.
[src:vertical-pod-autoscaling/resource-management-computing] This is correct if the intervening `...` code does not contain an early exit (`return`), the language does not have exceptions, and `open` is guaranteed to succeed.
[src:vertical-pod-autoscaling/resource-management-computing] However, it causes a resource leak if there is a return or exception, and causes an incorrect release of unacquired resource if `open` can fail.
[src:vertical-pod-autoscaling/resource-management-computing] There are two more fundamental problems: the acquisition-release pair is not adjacent (the release code must be written far from the acquisition code), and resource management is not encapsulated – the programmer must manually ensure that they are always paired.
[src:vertical-pod-autoscaling/resource-management-computing] In combination, these mean that acquisition and release must be explicitly paired, but cannot be placed together, thus making it easy for these to not be paired correctly.
[src:vertical-pod-autoscaling/resource-management-computing] This ensures correct release even if there is a return within the body or an exception thrown.
[src:vertical-pod-autoscaling/resource-management-computing] Further, note that the acquisition occurs *before* the `try` clause, ensuring that the `finally` clause is only executed if the `open` code succeeds (without throwing an exception), assuming that "no exception" means "success" (as is the case for `open` in Python).
[src:vertical-pod-autoscaling/resource-management-computing] While this ensures correct resource management, it fails to provide adjacency or encapsulation.
[src:vertical-pod-autoscaling/resource-management-computing] There are many variations in the implementation, and there are also significantly different approaches.
[src:vertical-pod-autoscaling/resource-management-computing] The most common approach to resource management across languages is to use unwind protection, which is called when execution exits a scope – by execution running off the end of the block, returning from within the block, or an exception being thrown.
[src:vertical-pod-autoscaling/resource-management-computing] This works for stack-managed resources, and is implemented in many languages, including C#, Common Lisp, Java, Python, Ruby, and Scheme.
[src:vertical-pod-autoscaling/resource-management-computing] The main problems with this approach is that the release code (most commonly in a `finally` clause) may be very distant from the acquisition code (it lacks *adjacency*), and that the acquisition and release code must always be paired by the caller (it lacks *encapsulation*).
[src:vertical-pod-autoscaling/resource-management-computing] An alternative, more imperative approach, is to write asynchronous code in direct style: acquire a resource, and then in the next line have a *deferred* release, which is called when the scope is exited – synchronous acquisition followed by asynchronous release.
[src:vertical-pod-autoscaling/resource-management-computing] This originated in C++ as the ScopeGuard class, by Andrei Alexandrescu and Petru Marginean in 2000, with improvements by Joshua Lehrer, and has direct language support in D via the `scope` keyword (ScopeGuardStatement), where it is one approach to exception safety, in addition to RAII (see below).
[src:vertical-pod-autoscaling/resource-management-computing] It has also been included in Go, as the `defer` statement.
[src:vertical-pod-autoscaling/resource-management-computing] This approach lacks encapsulation – one must explicitly match acquisition and release – but avoids having to create an object for each resource (code-wise, avoid writing a class for each type of resource).
[src:vertical-pod-autoscaling/resource-management-computing] In object-oriented programming, resources are encapsulated within objects that use them, such as a `file` object having a field whose value is a file descriptor (or more general file handle).
[src:vertical-pod-autoscaling/resource-management-computing] This allows the object to use and manage the resource without users of the object needing to do so.
[src:vertical-pod-autoscaling/resource-management-computing] However, there is a wide variety of ways that objects and resources can be related.
[src:vertical-pod-autoscaling/resource-management-computing] Firstly, there is the question of ownership: does an object *have* a resource?
[src:vertical-pod-autoscaling/resource-management-computing] Most common is to acquire a resource during object creation, and then explicitly release it via an instance method, commonly called `dispose`.
[src:vertical-pod-autoscaling/resource-management-computing] This is analogous to traditional file management (acquire during `open`, release by explicit `close`), and is known as the dispose pattern.
[src:vertical-pod-autoscaling/resource-management-computing] This is the basic approach used in several major modern object-oriented languages, including Java, C# and Python, and these languages have additional constructs to automate resource management.
[src:vertical-pod-autoscaling/resource-management-computing] However, even in these languages, more complex object relationships result in more complex resource management, as discussed below.
[src:vertical-pod-autoscaling/resource-management-computing] A natural approach is to make holding a resource be a class invariant: resources are acquired during object creation (specifically initialization), and released during object destruction (specifically finalization).
[src:vertical-pod-autoscaling/resource-management-computing] This is known as Resource Acquisition Is Initialization (RAII), and ties resource management to object lifetime, ensuring that live objects have all necessary resources.
[src:vertical-pod-autoscaling/resource-management-computing] Other approaches do not make holding the resource a class invariant, and thus objects may not have necessary resources (because they've not been acquired yet, have already been released, or are being managed externally), resulting in errors such as trying to read from a closed file.
[src:vertical-pod-autoscaling/resource-management-computing] This approach ties resource management to memory management (specifically object management), so if there are no memory leaks (no object leaks), there are no resource leaks.
[src:vertical-pod-autoscaling/resource-management-computing] RAII works naturally for heap-managed resources, not only stack-managed resources, and is composable: resources held by objects in arbitrarily complicated relationships (a complicated object graph) are released transparently simply by object destruction (so long as this is done properly!).
[src:vertical-pod-autoscaling/resource-management-computing] Firstly, because resources are expensive, it is desirable to release them promptly, so objects holding resources should be destroyed as soon as they become garbage (are no longer in use).
[src:vertical-pod-autoscaling/resource-management-computing] However, most modern automatic memory management is non-deterministic, making no guarantees that objects will be destroyed promptly or even at all!
[src:vertical-pod-autoscaling/resource-management-computing] This is because it is cheaper to leave some garbage allocated than to precisely collect each object immediately on its becoming garbage.
[src:vertical-pod-autoscaling/resource-management-computing] Secondly, releasing resources during object destruction means that an object must have a *finalizer* (in deterministic memory management known as a *destructor*) – the object cannot simply be deallocated – which significantly complicates and slows garbage collection.
[src:vertical-pod-autoscaling/resource-management-computing] When multiple objects rely on a single resource, resource management can be complicated.
[src:vertical-pod-autoscaling/resource-management-computing] A fundamental question is whether a "has a" relationship is one of *owning* another object (object composition), or *viewing* another object (object aggregation).
[src:vertical-pod-autoscaling/resource-management-computing] A common case is when one two objects are chained, as in pipe and filter pattern, the delegation pattern, the decorator pattern, or the adapter pattern.
[src:vertical-pod-autoscaling/resource-management-computing] If the second object (which is not used directly) holds a resource, is the first object (which is used directly) responsible for managing the resource?
[src:vertical-pod-autoscaling/resource-management-computing] This is generally answered identically to whether the first object *owns* the second object: if so, then the owning object is also responsible for resource management ("having a resource" is transitive), while if not, then it is not.
[src:vertical-pod-autoscaling/resource-management-computing] Further, a single object may "have" several other objects, owning some and viewing others.
[src:vertical-pod-autoscaling/resource-management-computing] Both cases are commonly found, and conventions differ.
[src:vertical-pod-autoscaling/resource-management-computing] In object aggregation, nothing needs to be done by the viewing object, as it is not responsible for the resource.
[src:vertical-pod-autoscaling/resource-management-computing] For example, in the Java Class Library, `Reader#close()` closes the underlying stream, and these can be chained.
[src:vertical-pod-autoscaling/resource-management-computing] For example, a `BufferedReader` may contain a `InputStreamReader`, which in turn contains a `FileInputStream`, and calling `close` on the `BufferedReader` in turn closes the `InputStreamReader`, which in turn closes the `FileInputStream`, which in turn releases the system file resource.
[src:vertical-pod-autoscaling/resource-management-computing] By contrast, in Python, a csv.reader does not own the `file` that it is reading, so there is no need (and it is not possible) to close the reader, and instead the `file` itself must be closed.
[src:vertical-pod-autoscaling/resource-management-computing] Various mechanisms exist to allow greater control of resource management.
[src:vertical-pod-autoscaling/resource-management-computing] For example, in the Google Closure Library, the `goog.Disposable` class provides a `registerDisposable` method to register other objects to be disposed with this object, together with various lower-level instance and class methods to manage disposal.
[src:vertical-pod-autoscaling/resource-management-computing] In structured programming, stack resource management is done simply by nesting code sufficiently to handle all cases.
[src:vertical-pod-autoscaling/resource-management-computing] This requires only a single return at the end of the code, and can result in heavily nested code if many resources must be acquired, which is considered an anti-pattern by some – the *Arrow Anti Pattern,* due to the triangular shape from the successive nesting.
[src:vertical-pod-autoscaling/resource-management-computing] One other approach, which allows early return but consolidates cleanup in one place, is to have a single exit return of a function, preceded by cleanup code, and to use goto to jump to the cleanup before exit.
[src:vertical-pod-autoscaling/resource-management-computing] This is infrequently seen in modern code, but occurs in some uses of C.
[src:vertical-pod-autoscaling/scalability] In an economic context, a scalable business model implies that a company can increase sales given increased resources.
[src:vertical-pod-autoscaling/scalability] For example, a package delivery system is scalable because more packages can be delivered by adding more delivery vehicles.
[src:vertical-pod-autoscaling/scalability] However, if all packages had to first pass through a single warehouse for sorting, the system would not be as scalable, because one warehouse can handle only a limited number of packages.
[src:vertical-pod-autoscaling/scalability] In computing, scalability is a characteristic of computers, networks, algorithms, networking protocols, programs and applications.
[src:vertical-pod-autoscaling/scalability] An example is a search engine, which must support increasing numbers of users, and the number of topics it indexes.
[src:vertical-pod-autoscaling/scalability] **Webscale** is a computer architectural approach that brings the capabilities of large-scale cloud computing companies into enterprise data centers.
[src:vertical-pod-autoscaling/scalability] In distributed systems, there are several definitions according to the authors, some considering the concepts of scalability a sub-part of elasticity, others as being distinct.
[src:vertical-pod-autoscaling/scalability] According to Marc Brooker: "a system is scalable in the range where marginal cost of additional workload is nearly constant." Serverless technologies fit this definition but you need to consider total cost of ownership not just the infra cost.
[src:vertical-pod-autoscaling/scalability] In mathematics, scalability mostly refers to closure under scalar multiplication.
[src:vertical-pod-autoscaling/scalability] In industrial engineering and manufacturing, scalability refers to the capacity of a process, system, or organization to handle a growing workload, adapt to increasing demands, and maintain operational efficiency.
[src:vertical-pod-autoscaling/scalability] A scalable system can effectively manage increased production volumes, new product lines, or expanding markets without compromising quality or performance.
[src:vertical-pod-autoscaling/scalability] In this context, scalability is a vital consideration for businesses aiming to meet customer expectations, remain competitive, and achieve sustainable growth.
[src:vertical-pod-autoscaling/scalability] Factors influencing scalability include the flexibility of the production process, the adaptability of the workforce, and the integration of advanced technologies.
[src:vertical-pod-autoscaling/scalability] By implementing scalable solutions, companies can optimize resource utilization, reduce costs, and streamline their operations.
[src:vertical-pod-autoscaling/scalability] Scalability in industrial engineering and manufacturing enables businesses to respond to fluctuating market conditions, capitalize on emerging opportunities, and thrive in an ever-evolving global landscape.
[src:vertical-pod-autoscaling/scalability] The Incident Command System (ICS) is used by emergency response agencies in the United States.
[src:vertical-pod-autoscaling/scalability] ICS can scale resource coordination from a single-engine roadside brushfire to an interstate wildfire.
[src:vertical-pod-autoscaling/scalability] The first resource on scene establishes command, with authority to order resources and delegate responsibility (managing five to seven officers, who will again delegate to up to seven, and on as the incident grows).
[src:vertical-pod-autoscaling/scalability] As an incident expands, more senior officers assume command.
[src:vertical-pod-autoscaling/scalability] Resources fall into two broad categories: horizontal and vertical.
[src:vertical-pod-autoscaling/scalability] Scaling horizontally (out/in) means adding or removing nodes, such as adding a new computer to a distributed software application.
[src:vertical-pod-autoscaling/scalability] An example might involve scaling out from one web server to three.
[src:vertical-pod-autoscaling/scalability] High-performance computing applications, such as seismic analysis and biotechnology, scale workloads horizontally to support tasks that once would have required expensive supercomputers.
[src:vertical-pod-autoscaling/scalability] Other workloads, such as large social networks, exceed the capacity of the largest supercomputer and can only be handled by scalable systems.
[src:vertical-pod-autoscaling/scalability] Exploiting this scalability requires software for efficient resource management and maintenance.
[src:vertical-pod-autoscaling/scalability] Scaling vertically (up/down) means adding resources to (or removing resources from) a single node, typically involving the addition of CPUs, memory or storage to a single computer.
[src:vertical-pod-autoscaling/scalability] Benefits to scale-up include avoiding increased management complexity, more sophisticated programming to allocate tasks among resources and handling issues such as throughput, latency, and synchronization across nodes.
[src:vertical-pod-autoscaling/scalability] Moreover some applications do not scale horizontally.
[src:vertical-pod-autoscaling/scalability] Network function virtualization defines these terms differently: scaling out/in is the ability to scale by adding/removing resource instances (e.g., virtual machine), whereas scaling up/down is the ability to scale by changing allocated resources (e.g., memory/CPU/storage capacity).
[src:vertical-pod-autoscaling/scalability] Scalability for databases requires that the database system be able to perform additional work given greater hardware resources, such as additional servers, processors, memory and storage.
[src:vertical-pod-autoscaling/scalability] Workloads have continued to grow and demands on databases have followed suit.
[src:vertical-pod-autoscaling/scalability] Algorithmic innovations include row-level locking and table and index partitioning.
[src:vertical-pod-autoscaling/scalability] Architectural innovations include shared-nothing and shared-everything architectures for managing multi-server configurations.
[src:vertical-pod-autoscaling/scalability] In the context of scale-out data storage, scalability is defined as the maximum storage cluster size which guarantees full data consistency, meaning there is only ever one valid version of stored data in the whole cluster, independently from the number of redundant physical data copies.
[src:vertical-pod-autoscaling/scalability] Clusters which provide "lazy" redundancy by updating copies in an asynchronous fashion are called 'eventually consistent'.
[src:vertical-pod-autoscaling/scalability] This type of scale-out design is suitable when availability and responsiveness are rated higher than consistency, which is true for many web file-hosting services or web caches (*if you want the latest version, wait some seconds for it to propagate*).
[src:vertical-pod-autoscaling/scalability] For all classical transaction-oriented applications, this design should be avoided.
[src:vertical-pod-autoscaling/scalability] Many open-source and even commercial scale-out storage clusters, especially those built on top of standard PC hardware and networks, provide eventual consistency only, such as some NoSQL databases like CouchDB and others mentioned above.
[src:vertical-pod-autoscaling/scalability] Write operations invalidate other copies, but often don't wait for their acknowledgements.
[src:vertical-pod-autoscaling/scalability] Read operations typically don't check every redundant copy prior to answering, potentially missing the preceding write operation.
[src:vertical-pod-autoscaling/scalability] The large amount of metadata signal traffic would require specialized hardware and short distances to be handled with acceptable performance (i.e., act like a non-clustered storage device or database).
[src:vertical-pod-autoscaling/scalability] It is often advised to focus system design on hardware scalability rather than on capacity.
[src:vertical-pod-autoscaling/scalability] It is typically cheaper to add a new node to a system in order to achieve improved performance than to partake in performance tuning to improve the capacity that each node can handle.
[src:vertical-pod-autoscaling/scalability] But this approach can have diminishing returns (as discussed in performance engineering).
[src:vertical-pod-autoscaling/scalability] For example: suppose 70% of a program can be sped up if parallelized and run on multiple CPUs instead of one.
[src:vertical-pod-autoscaling/scalability] Doubling the processing power has only sped up the process by roughly one-fifth.
[src:vertical-pod-autoscaling/scalability] If the whole problem was parallelizable, the speed would also double.
[src:vertical-pod-autoscaling/scalability] Therefore, throwing in more hardware is not necessarily the optimal approach.
[src:vertical-pod-autoscaling/scalability] In distributed systems, you can use Universal Scalability Law (USL) to model and to optimize scalability of your system.
[src:vertical-pod-autoscaling/scalability] Gunther and quantifies scalability based on parameters such as contention and coherency.
[src:vertical-pod-autoscaling/scalability] Contention refers to delay due to waiting or queueing for shared resources.
[src:vertical-pod-autoscaling/scalability] Coherence refers to delay for data to become consistent.
[src:vertical-pod-autoscaling/scalability] For example, having a high contention indicates sequential processing that could be parallelized, while having a high coherency suggests excessive dependencies among processes, prompting you to minimize interactions.
[src:vertical-pod-autoscaling/scalability] Also, with help of USL, you can, in advance, calculate the maximum effective capacity of your system: scaling up your system beyond that point is a waste.
[src:vertical-pod-autoscaling/workloads-autoscaling] With autoscaling, you can automatically update your workloads in one way or another.
[src:vertical-pod-autoscaling/workloads-autoscaling] This allows your cluster to react to changes in resource demand more elastically and efficiently.
[src:vertical-pod-autoscaling/workloads-autoscaling] In Kubernetes, you can *scale* a workload depending on the current demand of resources.
[src:vertical-pod-autoscaling/workloads-autoscaling] When you scale a workload, you can either increase or decrease the number of replicas managed by the workload, or adjust the resources available to the replicas in-place.
[src:vertical-pod-autoscaling/workloads-autoscaling] The first approach is referred to as *horizontal scaling*, while the second is referred to as *vertical scaling*.
[src:vertical-pod-autoscaling/workloads-autoscaling] There are manual and automatic ways to scale your workloads, depending on your use case.
[src:vertical-pod-autoscaling/workloads-autoscaling] Kubernetes supports *manual scaling* of workloads.
[src:vertical-pod-autoscaling/workloads-autoscaling] Horizontal scaling can be done using the `kubectl` CLI.
[src:vertical-pod-autoscaling/workloads-autoscaling] For vertical scaling, you need to *patch* the resource definition of your workload.
[src:vertical-pod-autoscaling/workloads-autoscaling] See below for examples of both strategies.
[src:vertical-pod-autoscaling/workloads-autoscaling] Kubernetes also supports *automatic scaling* of workloads, which is the focus of this page.
[src:vertical-pod-autoscaling/workloads-autoscaling] The concept of *Autoscaling* in Kubernetes refers to the ability to automatically update an object that manages a set of Pods (for example a Deployment).
[src:vertical-pod-autoscaling/workloads-autoscaling] In Kubernetes, you can automatically scale a workload horizontally using a HorizontalPodAutoscaler (HPA).
[src:vertical-pod-autoscaling/workloads-autoscaling] It is implemented as a Kubernetes API resource and a controller and periodically adjusts the number of replicas in a workload to match observed resource utilization such as CPU or memory usage.
[src:vertical-pod-autoscaling/workloads-autoscaling] There is a walkthrough tutorial of configuring a HorizontalPodAutoscaler for a Deployment.
[src:vertical-pod-autoscaling/workloads-autoscaling] You can automatically scale a workload vertically using a VerticalPodAutoscaler (VPA).
[src:vertical-pod-autoscaling/workloads-autoscaling] Unlike the HPA, the VPA doesn't come with Kubernetes by default, but is a an add-on that you or a cluster administrator may need to deploy before you can use it.
[src:vertical-pod-autoscaling/workloads-autoscaling] Once installed, it allows you to create CustomResourceDefinitions (CRDs) for your workloads which define *how* and *when* to scale the resources of the managed replicas.
[src:vertical-pod-autoscaling/workloads-autoscaling] installed to your cluster for the VPA to work.
[src:vertical-pod-autoscaling/workloads-autoscaling] As of Kubernetes 1.36, VPA does not support resizing pods in-place, but this integration is being worked on.
[src:vertical-pod-autoscaling/workloads-autoscaling] For manually resizing pods in-place, see Resize Container Resources In-Place.
[src:vertical-pod-autoscaling/workloads-autoscaling] For workloads that need to be scaled based on the size of the cluster (for example `cluster-dns` or other system components), you can use the *Cluster Proportional Autoscaler*.
[src:vertical-pod-autoscaling/workloads-autoscaling] Just like the VPA, it is not part of the Kubernetes core, but hosted as its own project on GitHub.
[src:vertical-pod-autoscaling/workloads-autoscaling] The Cluster Proportional Autoscaler watches the number of schedulable nodes and cores and scales the number of replicas of the target workload accordingly.
[src:vertical-pod-autoscaling/workloads-autoscaling] If the number of replicas should stay the same, you can scale your workloads vertically according to the cluster size using the *Cluster Proportional Vertical Autoscaler*.
[src:vertical-pod-autoscaling/workloads-autoscaling] The project is **currently in beta** and can be found on GitHub.
[src:vertical-pod-autoscaling/workloads-autoscaling] While the Cluster Proportional Autoscaler scales the number of replicas of a workload, the Cluster Proportional Vertical Autoscaler adjusts the resource requests for a workload (for example a Deployment or DaemonSet) based on the number of nodes and/or cores in the cluster.
[src:vertical-pod-autoscaling/workloads-autoscaling] It is also possible to scale workloads based on events, for example using the *Kubernetes Event Driven Autoscaler* (**KEDA**).
[src:vertical-pod-autoscaling/workloads-autoscaling] KEDA is a CNCF-graduated project enabling you to scale your workloads based on the number of events to be processed, for example the amount of messages in a queue.
[src:vertical-pod-autoscaling/workloads-autoscaling] There exists a wide range of adapters for different event sources to choose from.
[src:vertical-pod-autoscaling/workloads-autoscaling] Another strategy for scaling your workloads is to **schedule** the scaling operations, for example in order to reduce resource consumption during off-peak hours.
[src:vertical-pod-autoscaling/workloads-autoscaling] Similar to event driven autoscaling, such behavior can be achieved using KEDA in conjunction with its `Cron` scaler.
[src:vertical-pod-autoscaling/workloads-autoscaling] The `Cron` scaler allows you to define schedules (and time zones) for scaling your workloads in or out.
[src:vertical-pod-autoscaling/workloads-autoscaling] If scaling workloads isn't enough to meet your needs, you can also scale your cluster infrastructure itself.
[src:vertical-pod-autoscaling/workloads-autoscaling] Scaling the cluster infrastructure normally means adding or removing nodes.
[src:vertical-pod-autoscaling/workloads-autoscaling] Read Node autoscaling for more information.
